'''American English''' ('''AmE''', '''AE''', '''AmEng''', '''USEng''', '''en-US'''),<ref><code>en-US</code> is the [[language code]] for ''U.S. English'', as defined by [[ISO standard]]s (see [[ISO 639-1]] and [[ISO 3166-1 alpha-2]]) and [[Internet standard]]s (see [[IETF language tag]]).</ref> sometimes called '''United States English''' or '''U.S. English''',<ref>Plichta, Bartlomiej, and Dennis R. Preston (2005). "The /ay/s Have It: The Perception of /ay/ as a North-South Stereotype in the United States English." ''Acta Linguistica Hafniensia'' 37.1: 107-130.</ref><ref>Zentella, A. C. (1982). Spanish and English in contact in the United States: The Puerto Rican experience. Word, 33(1-2), 41.</ref> is the set of varieties of the [[English language]] native to the United States.<ref>{{cite book|last=Crystal|first=David|authorlink=David Crystal|year=1997|title=English as a Global Language|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-53032-6}}</ref>

English is the most widely spoken language in the United States and is the common language used by the federal government, to the extent that all laws and compulsory education are practiced in English. Although not an officially established language of the whole country, English is considered the ''[[de facto]]'' language and is given official status by 32 of the 50 state governments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.languagepolicy.net/archives/langleg.htm |title=Language Legislation in the U.S.A. |publisher=languagepolicy.net |date=1 February 2012 |author=Crawford, James |accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.us-english.org/view/1034 |title=U.S. English Efforts Lead West Virginia to Become 32nd State to Recognize English as Official Language |publisher=us-english.org |deadurl=yes |accessdate=13 May 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401151700/http://us-english.org/view/1034 |archivedate=1 April 2016 |df= }}</ref> As an example, while both Spanish and English have equivalent status in the local courts of [[Puerto Rico]], under federal law, English is the official language for any matters being referred to the [[United States district court]] for the territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/48/864 |title=48 U.S. Code § 864 - Appeals, certiorari, removal of causes, etc.; use of English language &#124; LII / Legal Information Institute |publisher=Law.cornell.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref>

The use of English in the United States is a result of [[British colonization of the Americas|English and British colonization of the Americas]]. The first wave of English-speaking settlers arrived in North America during the 17th century, followed by further migrations in the 18th and 19th centuries. Since then, American English has developed into new dialects, in some cases under the influence of [[West African languages|West African]] and [[Indigenous languages of the Americas|Native American languages]], [[German language|German]], [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[Irish language|Irish]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], and other languages of successive waves of immigrants to the United States.

American English varieties form a linguistic continuum of dialects more similar to each other than to English dialects of other countries, including some common pronunciations and other features found nationwide.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mtd3a-56ysUC&pg|title= A Handbook of Varieties of English|author-first=William A.|author-last=Kretzchmar|editor-first=Bernd|editor-last=Kortmann|editor2-first=Edgar W.|editor2-last=Schneider|publisher=Mouton de Gruyter|location=Berlin/New York|year=2004|pages=262–263|isbn= 9783110175325}}</ref> Any [[North American English]] [[accent (sociolinguistics)|accent]] perceived as free of noticeably local, ethnic, or cultural [[markedness|markers]] is popularly called [[General American|"General" or "Standard" American]], a fairly uniform standard of broadcast mass media and the highly educated. Otherwise, according to Labov, with the major exception of [[Southern American English]], regional accents throughout the country are not yielding to this standard,<ref>Labov, William (2010). "[http://www.cogsci.msu.edu/DSS/2011-2012/Labov/POLC%20Chapters%201-3.pdf Chapter 1]".''The Politics of Language Change: Dialect Divergence in America''. The University of Virginia Press. Pre-publication draft. p. 55.</ref> and historical and present linguistic evidence does not support the notion of there being one single "mainstream" American accent.<ref>Labov, William (2012). ''Dialect diversity in America: The politics of language change''. University of Virginia Press. pp. 1-2.</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mtd3a-56ysUC&pg|title= A Handbook of Varieties of English|author-first=William A.|author-last=Kretzchmar|editor-first=Bernd|editor-last=Kortmann|editor2-first=Edgar W.|editor2-last=Schneider|publisher=Mouton de Gruyter|location=Berlin/New York|year=2004|page=262|isbn= 9783110175325}}</ref> On the contrary, the sound of American English continues to evolve, with some local accents disappearing, but several larger regional accents emerging.<ref name="PBS">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/speak/ahead/|title=Do You Speak American: What Lies Ahead|accessdate=2007-08-15|publisher=PBS}}</ref>

==Varieties== <!-- This section is linked from [[Huckleberry Hound]]; Northeastern American English redirects here -->
{{Main|Regional vocabularies of American English|North American English regional phonology}}

While written American English is largely standardized across the country, there are several recognizable variations in the spoken language, both in pronunciation and in vernacular vocabulary. The regional sounds of present-day American English are reportedly engaged in a complex phenomenon of "both convergence and divergence": some accents are homogenizing and [[accent levelling|levelling]], while others are diversifying and deviating further away from one another.<ref>Labov, William. 2012. Dialect diversity in America: the politics of language change. Charlottesville: University of Virginia Press.</ref> In 2010, [[William Labov]] summarized the current state of regional American accents as follows:<ref name="Labov 2010">Labov, William (2010). ''[http://www.cogsci.msu.edu/DSS/2011-2012/Labov/POLC%20Chapters%201-3.pdf The Politics of Language Change: Dialect Divergence in America]''. The University of Virginia Press. Pre-publication draft. p. 53-4.</ref>

Some regional American English has undergone "vigorous new sound changes" since the mid-nineteenth century onwards, spawning relatively recent [[Mid-Atlantic American English|Mid-Atlantic]] (centered on [[Philadelphia]] and [[Baltimore]]), [[Western Pennsylvania English|Western Pennsylvania]] (centered on [[Pittsburgh]]), [[Inland Northern American English|Inland Northern]] (centered on [[Chicago]], [[Detroit]], and the [[Great Lakes region]]), [[Midland American English|Midland]] (centered on [[Indianapolis]], [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], and [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]) and [[Western American English|Western regional accents]], all of which "are now more different from each other than they were fifty or a hundred years ago". Meanwhile, distinguishing features of the [[Eastern New England English|Eastern New England]] (centered on [[Boston]]) and [[New York City English|New York City accents]] appear to be stable. "On the other hand, dialects of many smaller cities have receded in favor of the new regional patterns";<ref name="Labov 2010"/> for example, the traditional accents of [[Charleston, SC|Charleston]] and of [[Cincinnati, OH|Cincinnati]] have given way to the Midland regional accent, and of [[St. Louis, MO|St. Louis]] now approaches the sounds of an Inland Northern or Midland accent. At the same time, the [[Southern American English|Southern regional accent]], despite the huge population it covers,<ref name="PBS"/> "is on the whole slowly receding due to cultural stigma: younger speakers everywhere in the South are shifting away from the [[markedness|marked]] features of Southern speech". Finally, the [[High Tider|"Hoi Toider" dialect]] shows the paradox of receding among younger speakers in the islands of North Carolina's [[Outer Banks]], yet strengthening in the islands of the [[Chesapeake Bay]].

